The production of mRNA is governed by the differential equation-         \begin{align}        \frac{dm_a}{dt} = b_a(P^{a}_{0,0} + \alpha P^{a}_{1,0}) -  \gamma_{ma} m_a \\        \frac{dm_r}{dt} = b_r(P^{r}_{0,0} + \alpha P^{r}_{1,0}) -  \gamma_{mr} m_r        \end{align}
Here, $P^{a/r}_{0,0}, P^{a/r}_{1,0}$ are also variables, and the differential equation above is coupled to the rate equation governing promoter binding reactions for LacI and AraC.       We assume that these reactions are fast reactions and attain equilibrium very quickly. Thus, we can write-        \begin{align}       P^{a/r}_{1,0} = k_1 a_2 P^{a/r}_{0,0} \\       P^{a/r}_{i,1} = 2k_2 r_4 P^{a/r}_{i,0} \\       P^{a/r}_{i,2} = k_2 r_4 P^{a/r}_{i,1} \\       \end{align}       The dimerisation and tetramerisation reactions give us-        \begin{align}       \begin{split}       a_2 & = k_{da} a^2 \\        r_2 & = k_{dr1} r^2 \\        r_4 & = k_{dr2} r^2_2 \\ & = k_{dr2} k^2_{dr1} r^4\\       \end{split}       \end{align}       We define $c_a := k_1 k_{da}$ and $c_R := k_2 k_{dr2} k^2_{dr1}$.

